## Attribution

This project — QTK ("Qalarc Token Killer", also a backronym for "Quantised
Token Killer") — derives its core thesis and the TOML filter DSL format
from:

  RTK (Rust Token Killer)
  https://github.com/rtk-ai/rtk
  https://rtk-ai.app
  Copyright (c) Patrick Szymkowiak, Florian Bruniaux, Adrien Eppling
                and RTK contributors.
  Licensed under the Apache License, Version 2.0.

RTK is the mature, production project. It supports 13 AI coding tools
(Claude Code, Cursor, Gemini CLI, Copilot, OpenCode, Codex, Windsurf,
Cline, Hermes, …), ships a 100+ command filter corpus, has its own
documented telemetry-with-consent policy, and runs across Linux, macOS,
and Windows. It proved at scale that AI-agent tool output is
deterministically compressible without an LLM. **If you are running
any agent other than opencode, use RTK.**

QTK exists because the opencode plugin surface lets us hook
`tool.execute.after` in-process, which removes the per-call subprocess
fork and the system-prompt overhead that any external-CLI tool
(including RTK) necessarily carries. That trade-off only makes sense
when you're already committed to opencode. For everything else, RTK is
both broader and more battle-tested.

QTK's TOML filter DSL is a clean-room implementation that intentionally
shares user-facing TOML keys with RTK so RTK filters round-trip without
modification. No RTK source code is vendored in this repository.
Filters imported via `scripts/import-rtk-filters.ts` retain their
original Apache-2.0 attribution as a comment in the file header.

Per Apache-2.0 §4(b), this file constitutes the NOTICE for QTK's
incorporation of architectural ideas from RTK.
